nistrators in the first part of the 20th century, as a dramatic decline in population was observed in many regions. However, the total demise of Melanesian populations predicted by some never happened; on the contrary, a rapid population increase took place for the second part of the 20th century. This volume explores relationships between human fertility and reproduction, subsistence systems, the symbolic use of ideas of fertility and reproduction in linking landscape to individuals and populations, in Melanesian societies, past and present. It thus offers an important contribution to our understanding of the implications of social and economic change for reproduction and fertility in the broadest sense.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aDemographic anthropologyzMelanesia. 0aFertility, HumanzMelanesia. 0aHuman reproductionzMelanesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAtaka, Yuji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayliss-Smith, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnemère, Pascale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemian, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDwyer, Peter D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGosden, C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingston, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemonnier, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinnegal, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhtsuka, Ryutaro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Hanlon, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct